Housedivers is organizing a raffle in which they will draw 3 names out of 120 people to win a car, a vacation, or a small gift at random. What are the odds in favor of Earl Smith, who is one of the names drawn? Please express your answer as a fraction reduced to lowest terms.
To calculate the odds in favor of Earl Smith being drawn, we first determine the total number of ways Earl can be drawn along with any two other people out of the 119 remaining participants. This can be calculated using combinations:

{eq}_{120}C_{3} = \frac{120!}{3!(120-3)!} = \frac{120!}{3! \times 117!} = \frac{120 \times 119 \times 118}{3 \times 2 \times 1} = 28,700{/eq}

Next, we calculate the number of ways Earl doesn't win, which includes him being one of the two people not winning:

{eq}_{120}C_{2} = \frac{120!}{2!(120-2)!} = \frac{120!}{2! \times 118!} = \frac{120 \times 119}{2 \times 1} = 7,140{/eq}

The probability of Earl not winning is then:

{eq}\dfrac{\text{Number of ways Earl doesn't win}}{\text{Total number of ways}} = \dfrac{7,140}{28,700} = \dfrac{3}{12} = \dfrac{1}{4}{/eq}

The probability of Earl winning is the complement of not winning:

{eq}\mathbb{P}(\text{Earl Wins}) = 1 - \mathbb{P}(\text{Earl Doesn't Win}) = 1 - \dfrac{1}{4} = \dfrac{3}{4}{/eq}

Converting this probability to odds in favor of Earl Winning:

{eq}\text{Odds in Favor} = \dfrac{\text{Probability of Winning}}{\text{Probability of Losing}} = \dfrac{\dfrac{3}{4}}{\dfrac{1}{4}} = 3:1{/\eq}

Therefore, the odds in favor of Earl Smith winning the raffle are 3 to 1.

