The way to find the answer in the question is through listing and counting method. Each $\,n-$th layer can contribute either '$\,4\,$'' or $\,\,'10''\,$ or $\,\,'19''\,$ to the total height of the tower. Interestingly, this leads us to $$X = 4\left|\text{Number of 4'' layers} \right| + 10 \left|\text{Number of 10'' layers} \right| + 19 \left|\text{Number of 19'' layers}\right| $$</think>Let the number of 4'' bricks to be used be $\,x\,$, the number of 10'' bricks be be $\,y\,$, and the number of 19'' bricks be be $\,z\,$. The total number of bricks is :
\begin{eqnarray}
\left|x\right| + \left|y\right| + \left|z\right| = 94
\end{eqnarray}
One can use stars and bars to enumerate the number of solution to this equation.

\begin{eqnarray}
\sum _{k=0}^{94} {94 \choose k} = 2^{94}
\end{eqnarray}
One can further simplify the enumeration to be 2 * 28^4 by noting that the number of 19'' bricks, $\left|x\right|$ is either odd or even.  If the number of bricks of a certain height is odd, then ending up with the same height would be missing one brick of that height.  The binaries are shown as:
\begin{eqnarray}
x &=& 0,1,2,3,...,94\\
y &=& 0,1,2,3,...,94\\
z &=& 0,1,2,3,...,94
\end{eqnarray}
After filtering, $\left|x\right|$ is one more than half or half of the remain.
We can enumerate $x$ = 0, 2, 4, 6, 8, ..., 92, 94.
We can enumerate $x$ = 1, 3, 5, 7, 9, ..., 93.
Hence, the summation in the author's solution is split into $\left|x\right|$ even and $\left|x\right|$ odd:

\begin{eqnarray}
\sum _{k=0}^{47} {57 \choose 2k} = 2^{55} &\,,& \,\, \left|x\right| = 2n\\
\sum _{k=0}^{46} {57 \choose 2k + 1} = 2^{55} &&, \,\,\left|x\right| = 2n + 1\\
\end{eqnarray}
Summing both over, we get $2 * 2^{56} = \boxed{ 1238096 } $number of possible towers
Therefore, $\color{blue}{\text{There are 1,238,096 different tower heights that can be achieved with 94 bricks.}}$
</answer>

